entries.fullText:
To commemorate the four hundredth anniversary of the
discovery of America, will be held on the shore of Lake
Michigan, in the City of Chicago, and will be opened on the
first day of May, 1893, and closed on the 30th day of October
following.
Jackson Park and Midway Plaisance--the Exposition site
-are in the southeastern part of Chicago, and embrace 666
acres, with a frontage of about a mile and a half on Lake
Michigan. Forty-five miles of boulevard connect the site
with the general park system, which embraces fifteen or
more parks, aggregating 2,000 acres.
entries.summaryText: Description of the location and dates of the Columbian Exposition in Chicago, including details about the site and surrounding parks.

entries.fullText:
ART BUILDING. It is the intention to locate on the Lake
Front Park, near the heart of the city, the building required
for Department "K," embracing Fine Arts, Pictorial, Plastic
and Decorative, and also a portion of Department "L,"
at a cost of $500,000.
entries.summaryText: Plans to build the Art Building in Lake Front Park for the Fine Arts, Pictorial, Plastic, and Decorative departments.

entries.fullText:
THE WOMEN'S BUILDING. The President of the Board
of Lady Managers quickly discovered in the sketch submitted
by Miss Sophia G, Hayden that harmony of grouping
and gracefulness of details which indicate the architectural
scholar, and to her was awarded the first prize of a thousand
dollars, and also the execution of the design. The principal
facade has an extreme length of 400 feet, the depth of the
Building being half this distance.
entries.summaryText: Details about the Women's Building at the Columbian Exposition, including the awarding of the design to Sophia G. Hayden.

entries.fullText:
THE GOVERNMENT BUILDING. Located near the Lake
shore, south of the main lagoon and of the area reserved for
the foreign nations and the several States, in the Government
Exhibit Building. It is classic in style, and bears a string resemblance
to the National Museum and other Government
buildings at Washington. It covers an area of 350 by 420 feet,
is constructed of iron, brick and glass, and cost $400,000.
entries.summaryText: Description of the Government Exhibit Building at the Columbian Exposition, including its location and appearance.

entries.fullText:
HORTICULTURAL BUILDING. The building is 1,000 feet
long, with and extreme width of 286 feet. The plan is a central
pavilion with two end pavilions, each connected to the
center pavilion by front and rear curtains, forming two interior
courts, each 88 by 270 feet.
entries.summaryText: Details about the Horticultural Building at the Columbian Exposition, including its dimensions and layout.

entries.fullText:
THE ELECTRICAL BUILDING. The Electrical Building,
the seat of perhaps the most novel and brilliant exhibit in
the whole Exposition, is 345 feet wide and 700 feet long, the
major axis running north and south. The south front is on
ther great Quadrangle or Court: the north front faces the
lagoon; the east front is opposite the Manufactures Building
and the west faces the Mines Building.
entries.summaryText: Details about the Electrical Building at the Columbian Exposition, including its location and notable exhibits.

entries.fullText:
THE HALL OF MINES AND MINING. Located between
the Electricity and Transportation Building is the Mines
and Mining Building. This building is 700 feet long and 350
feet wide. The galleries are 60 feet wide by 25 feet high
from the ground floor, and are all lighted on the sides by large
windows, and from above by a high clearstory.
entries.summaryText: Details about the Mines and Mining Building at the Columbian Exposition, including its location and features.

entries.fullText:
ADMINISTRATION BUILDING. The Administration
Building is pronounced the gem and crown of the Exposition
palaces. It is located at the west end of the great
court in the southern part of the site looking eastward, and
at its rear are the transportation facilities and depots. The
most conspicuous object which will attract the gaze of visitors
on reaching the grounds is the gilded dome of this
lofty building. The imposing edifice will cost about
$450,000. The architect is Richard M. Hunt, of New-York,
President of the American Institute of Architects. It covers
and area of 260 feet square , and consists of four pavilions
84 feet square, one at each of the four angles of the square,
and connected by a great central dome 120 feet in diameter
and 220 feet in height.

MACHINERY BUILDING, of which Peabody & Stearns, of
Boston, are the architects, has been pronounced by many
architects second only to the Administration Building in the
magnificence of its appearance. This building measures
850 by 500 feet, and, with Machinery Annex and power
house, will cost about $1,200,000. It is located at the extreme
south end of the park, midway between the shore of
Lake Michigan and the west line of the park. It is just
south of the Administration Building, and west, across a
lagoon, from the Agriculture Building.
entries.summaryText: Details about the Administration and Machinery Buildings at the Columbian Exposition, including their architects, cost, and location.

entries.fullText:
THE FORESTRY BUILDING. The Forestry Building is
in appearance the most unique of all the Exposition structures.
Its dimensions are 200 by 500 feet. On all four sides of
the building is a veranda, supporting the roof of which is a
colonnade consisting of a series of columns composed of three
tree-trunks each 25 feet in length, one of them from 16 to 20
inches in diameter and the others smaller. All of these
trunks, are left in their natural state, with bark undisturbed.
entries.summaryText: Details about the Forestry Building at the Columbian Exposition, including its unique appearance and dimensions.

entries.fullText:
THE FISHERIES BUILDING. The Fisheries Building
embraces a large central structure with two smaller polygonal
buildings connected with it on each end by arcades.
The extreme length of the building is 1,100 feet and the
width 200 feet.
entries.summaryText: Details about the Fisheries Building at the Columbian Exposition, including its size and layout.

entries.fullText: The missing steamer, City of Peking, thirteen days overdue from Yokohoma, came in this afternoon in town of the special tugs Vigiland and Active. A broken shaft, as surmised, was the cause of the delay, and she has been seventeen days under sail, making her way slowly across the Pacific. The steamer San Juan, sent out only yesterday on a search expedition, passed her during the night, but early this morning the tug Vigiland forty miles out sighted the Peking, and soon had her in tow. As it was very rough just outside the Golden Gate, the steamer was not brought in until this afternoon. Then Telegraph Hill and the entire water front, was black with people who witnessed her arrival. Fully twenty thousand voices cheered when she came abreast of the city front. A visit to the vessel showed, as suspected, that the shaft was broken, and broken in the sleeve very near the propellor, in a position that could not be reached. The accident occurred at 7 o'clock on the morning on January 21st, when ten days out from Yokohoma. She at once proceeded to make this port under sail. It was impossible to repair the shaft and the propellor was nearly lost, hanging somewhat loosely behind, and acting as a drag. The entire distance, to within sight of port, was made under sail. The best days record was 119 miles, and she was seventeen days under sail. The northern course was taken, in the hope that she might meet the China, but no vessel was sighted until off this port. As a somewhat zigzag course had to be taken under sail the entire distance traversed was longer than that taken by a vessel under steam, being 1,340 miles. Everybody on board was well and the steamer looked as trim and neat as though nothing had happened. The Pacific mail officers cursed loud and deep over the hard luck that led the San Juan to miss the Peking. Spreckles, who is always fortunate in finding vessels, will clean up a large amount of salvage.
entries.summaryText: The City of Peking steamer arrived in San Francisco after being seventeen days under sail due to a broken shaft near the propellor. The steamer was cheered by twenty thousand people upon arrival and Spreckles will clean up a large amount of salvage.

Mrs. Greenleaf on her return in April
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony went to church, visited the state I. School, and discussed plans with Miss Craig. She returned home to find Mrs. Sanford, Hallowell, Smithe, daughter, and Mrs. Blackall planning a reception for Mrs. Greenleaf.

entries.fullText:
[?] celebrates her 25th
anniversary this day - And May
Wright Sewall is to be with them
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony mentions that someone is celebrating their 25th anniversary and May Wright Sewall will be with them.

entries.fullText:
May Wright Sewall arrived
at 9 A.M. from New York
had goodly number of women
at Chamber of Commerce at
3 P.M. & Prof & Mrs. Lattiman - Mrs.
Morse - Shields - Hallowell & Willis in
evening - & left on the 10.40 train
entries.summaryText: May Wright Sewall arrived from New York and had a meeting with a good number of women at the Chamber of Commerce. She also met with Prof, Mrs. Lattiman, Mrs. Morse, Shields, Hallowell, and Willis in the evening before leaving on the 10.40 train.

entries.fullText:
The clouds do not lift from
my spirit - am simply overwhelmed
with feeling that I can't see my way
through the work before me
After dinner went to S.I.S. to the
Laundry - Tailor & mending room - two girls
schools - Miss Purcell's Miss Parmalee's -
talked patching the boys shirts - poor earing
with Miss Cray - & called on [?]
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony went to S.I.S. to visit the Laundry, Tailor, and mending room, and talked about patching boys' shirts with Miss Purcell and Miss Parmalee. She also had a conversation with Miss Cray and called on someone.

entries.fullText:
Edward Perry -- grandson of J. Thayer - &
nephew of Mrs Mary Sanford died to day --
Mrs Mary Allen - King - Principal of
Miss Allen's Seminary in Allen St- Rochester
in the early days - died to day aged 94.
Our dear Mother Laser on 13 years ago to
day at 86, 4 months -
entries.summaryText: Edward Perry, grandson of J. Thayer and nephew of Mrs Mary Sanford, died. Mrs Mary Allen-King, Principal of Miss Allen's Seminary in Allen St-Rochester in the early days, died aged 94. It is also the 13th anniversary of the death of Mother Laser who died at 86 years and 4 months.

entries.fullText:
Went State I. School - 9. A.M. to
Catholic Service - Father Harrington -
- Manager O'grady there - and we had a
long talk, over matters of the institution -
- took dinner in girls Department - visited Mrs
Meldrum - Walter [Om?ldy] - Mr Garnett
spoke to boys on Lincoln - at 3.P.M - had
talk with Manager Desmond -
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony visits State I. School, has a long talk with Father Harrington and Manager O'grady, visits Mrs. Meldrum, and talks with Manager Desmond.

entries.fullText:
Mary & self called on Mrs
Greenleaf - & in P.M. went
Ignorance Club and heard Mrs
Oscar Craig read paper on
Missions - freezing at home - wrote
letters in evening - a letter from darling
Rachel enclosing $150. check to help
me out on rent - she said - it
overwhelmed me with gratitude !!
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony visits Mrs. Greenleaf, attends the Ignorance Club and hears Mrs. Oscar Craig read a paper on Missions, and receives a generous check from Rachel to help with rent.

entries.fullText:
Went to Dentist Requa's -
then to State School to see the
boys patch and darn - all cross threading
in the old fashion way - showed them
how to put a patch on instead -
- then had a talk with Mr Curtin -
the Steward - It is very hard
to get under the [?] and between the
lines - every employee fears to tell
the exact state of things -
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony goes to the dentist, visits State School to teach the boys how to patch and darn, and has a talk with Mr. Curtin, the Steward.

entries.fullText:
Mrs Byum went to S.I.S.
this A.M. with me - & taught
the girls teacher how to darn
stockings staid to dinner
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony goes to S.I.S. with Mrs. Byum and teaches the girls' teacher how to darn stockings.

entries.fullText:
Went State Ind. School.
at 2. P.M. to find the
Manager's Meeting adjourned
till Sunday P.M --
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony goes to State Ind. School and finds the Manager's Meeting adjourned until Sunday.

entries.fullText:
Mrs Greenleafs reception
this evening --
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony attends Mrs. Greenleaf's reception in the evening.

entries.fullText:
Reception to Mrs. Greenleaf
at Chamber Common - this evening
given by the P. E. Church of Rochester -
fully 600 passed Mrs. G. & greeted
her return home - a fine time
though the rain fell up to
the last minute - before eight oclock
Oh no - this was [?] night
entries.summaryText: Attended a reception for Mrs. Greenleaf in Rochester.

entries.fullText:
Went to State Industrial School
- Protestant Girls Sunday School -
then " P.M. Service - Wm. Seward
speaking - Board of Managers
Meeting at 4.Oclock - and held till
after seven - new bylaws adopted
Mr Tom. Raines - & talk of new Cook
Home - selected by men - &c
entries.summaryText: Attended church services and a board meeting at State Industrial School.

entries.fullText:
at 11 - N.Y. State Ex. Com.
met Powers Hotel Parlor - to
decide on Con. Con. Campaign -
-
entries.summaryText: Attended a meeting at Powers Hotel Parlor to discuss the Con. Con. Campaign.

entries.fullText:
- In the hurry of packing -
called at Mrs Gannetts - Dr's
Dolley and Learing called - to tell
J. M. Parker going to upset new
Ed. & Industrial Union -
Took 9.41 - P.M. train - Sister Mary
went depot with me -
entries.summaryText: Received a visit from Dr's Dolley and Learing and was informed of J. M. Parker's plans to upset the new Ed. & Industrial Union.

entries.fullText:
Took breakfast - Cleveland Ohio
Station - reached Warren O.
10. A.M. - Hon. E.B. Taylor's -
Harriet Taylor Uptons - dinner
at Presbyterian Church Parlors -
- meeting & talk at Episcopal parlors
at 2 -
entries.summaryText: Traveled to Warren O. and attended a meeting and dinner at Hon. E.B. Taylor's.

entries.fullText:
[?] day at Warren-
- thought out points in
Church and took Erie train
4.41 - P.M. for Cincinnati -
Went to bed at 7 and put in
a good long nights sleep
till 6 - A.M. Friday --
entries.summaryText: Spent the day in Warren and traveled to Cincinnati in the evening.

entries.fullText:
Mrs. O Orken
arrived Erie R.R. 6.20 A.M.
- Had good sized &
best class audience & made
a tolerably fair speech
entries.summaryText: Mrs. O Orken arrived and gave a speech.

entries.fullText:
Sent several notes out
to a Luncheon Party of 12-
at table - and
took train at 2 P.M. -
reaching Indianapolis at 8- ish
Rachel Foster - Mrs Sewell & self
talked over matters
entries.summaryText: Sent notes for a luncheon party and talked with Rachel Foster and Mrs Sewell.

entries.fullText:
Rachel & self took train
at 11 A.M. & reached Chicago
at 5:30 she had to wait till
9.45 for train- & I went to the
cousins - Dickinson - Melissa & [?]
still in Florida - Charles
& others - at home - -
entries.summaryText: Traveled to Chicago with Rachel and visited family members.

entries.fullText:
The World's Fair Opening = &
I found [?] friends in the
Woman's Building - Mrs. Palmer's address
very fine - covering full equality
for women
entries.summaryText: Attended the World's Fair Opening and heard Mrs. Palmer's speech on equality for women.

Reached Delaware - Ohio -
at 10. A.M. - stopped with
Mrs Croy - Mrs. D.T. Upton
came at 3. P.M -
entries.summaryText: Journal entry from May 9, 1893. Arrived in Delaware, Ohio and stayed with Mrs Croy. Mrs. D.T. Upton arrived later in the day.

entries.fullText:
Ohio State W.S.A. Con -
Delaware - spoke this
evening
entries.summaryText: Spoke at Ohio State W.S.A. Con in Delaware

entries.fullText:
Left Delaware at 10.50 -&
reached Chicago at 8.55 -&
went to Dickinsons - Walton Flats
found niece Lucy E. there
entries.summaryText: Visited Dickinsons in Walton Flats and found niece Lucy E. there

entries.fullText:
Took up quarters at the
Palmer House - room 373 -
on European plan -
Rachel & Mrs. Sewall & clerks there
entries.summaryText: Checked in at Palmer House and met Rachel, Mrs. Sewall, and clerks

entries.fullText:
At Palmer House - room 373-
rose at 6 and breakfasted with
Mrs. Coonley - her girl Hilda
fitted (to repair) garnet velvet-
In P.M. attend Woman's Club at
Atheneum Building - spoke to them
of laws for wives
entries.summaryText: Had breakfast with Mrs. Coonley and attended Woman's Club at Atheneum Building

entries.fullText:
rose at 7 A.M. and went
to breakfast - with cousins
Albert & Charles Dickinson
entries.summaryText: Had breakfast with cousins Albert & Charles Dickinson

entries.fullText:
Am to speak this [?] in the
Worlds Congress of Representative Women
on The Value of Organization in
respect to Political Equality -
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony is scheduled to speak at the Worlds Congress of Representative Women on the value of organization in respect to political equality.

entries.fullText: Rev. Anna's sermon splendid --
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony thought Rev. Anna's sermon was splendid.

entries.fullText:
Hull House - Jane Addams
Dinner at 6 - & speech in evg - blundered
- & lost this evening - Reception &
dinner at Mrs Wm Thayer Browns -
- Mr. B. drove me to Mr. Higenbothoms
to find my engagement with the
girl's literary club wasn't until Friday
June 2d - -
entries.summaryText: Dinner with Jane Addams, lost something, and attended a reception and dinner at Mrs. Wm Thayer Browns.

entries.fullText:
Mrs. Geo. D. Carpenters at -
dinner - with Rachel & her little
Miriam - a delightful company at
Mrs Coonleys - evening - brother D.R.
sister Annie & Maude there - also Fanny
Brown Jerome - niece Mattie's sister -
Rachel & self - left at Mrs Coonley
sister Mary occupied my room
at the Palmer -
entries.summaryText: Dinner at Mrs. Coonleys with Rachel and her daughter, and a delightful evening with family and friends.

entries.fullText:
at Palmer - tried to get
packed & moved to dear
Mrs Coonleys but failed
entries.summaryText: Attempted to move to Mrs. Coonleys but failed.

entries.fullText:
Finished packing & sent trunk
to Mrs Coonley's - spoke at
3 P.M. at Religious Press Congress-
on "Moral Leadership of Religious Press -
- too funny! - but I told them the [?]
that it had always led backward
not forward - Mrs De Voe.
there & took me to her house
in Harvey -
entries.summaryText: Finished packing and sent trunk to Mrs. Coonleys, spoke at the Religious Press Congress, and went to Mrs. De Voe's house in Harvey.

entries.fullText: - at Mrs De-Voes - spoke in tent to 3,000 in P.M & in M.E. - Baptist & Cong. churches in evening - dear ever ready Anna Shaw helping me out by speaking - half the hour at each place - Old Soldiers & the Harvey Band escorted me from church to church
entries.summaryText: Spoke in tent to 3,000 in P.M & in M.E. - Baptist & Cong. churches in evening - dear ever ready Anna Shaw helping me out by speaking - half the hour at each place - Old Soldiers & the Harvey Band escorted me from church to church

entries.fullText: quite Hoarse - reached Mrs. Coonley's near noon - & found all were at the fair grounds - so had a quiet day -
entries.summaryText: Reached Mrs. Coonley's near noon - & found all were at the fair grounds - so had a quiet day -

entries.fullText: noon. Day - Women's Daily - Woman's [?if??rence] versus Political Power'. - had fine audience - met Rachel & Miller -
entries.summaryText: Had fine audience - met Rachel & Miller -

entries.fullText: At Mrs Coonly's all the morning - resting & writing - reception in P.M. in honor of Mrs Palmer & Mrs Henrotin at the Lexington - splendid company Sister Mary called at Mr C this evg - raining hard -, Mr Maybe - Ed Christian's Union added to Mrs Coonleys guests
entries.summaryText: Reception in P.M. in honor of Mrs Palmer & Mrs Henrotin at the Lexington - splendid company Sister Mary called at Mr C this evg - raining hard -, Mr Maybe - Ed Christian's Union added to Mrs Coonleys guests

speak - assembly room - Woman's

Bed at Mrs E.E. Loomis - 29 [?]

entries.fullText: [?] Hull House - again -

Mrs Coonleys Dine to
Edgewater & dinner party -
of 20 - beside her family -

people: Mrs Coonly - Miss Root - Mrs Avery - Prof. Todd - and Prentice

Buffalo Bill show in

entries.fullText:
This day rounds My dear
sister Guelma's 75th year - she
has been gone from our sight
since Nov. 11.73
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony remembers her sister Guelma on her 75th birthday.

entries.fullText:
Left Glen Cove at 2 P.M.
met Mrs Carrie Lane Chapman
at Park Hotel - dined - &
took 9 P.M. train for
Rochester - didn't go down
to State school --
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony left Glen Cove and met with Mrs. Carrie Lane Chapman at Park Hotel before taking a train to Rochester.

entries.fullText:
at home - found Mrs
Tullam hadn't done
a thing to my dresses -
took the 6.30 P.M. train
for Chicago -
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony was at home and found out that Mrs. Tullam hadn't done anything to her dresses before taking a train to Chicago.

entries.fullText:
Landed Chicago -
about 11. oclock -
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony arrived in Chicago at around 11 o'clock.

entries.fullText:
at Mrs Sewalls reception
this evg - met many
of our Congress
friends -
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony attended Mrs. Sewall's reception and met many of their Congress friends.

entries.fullText:
Read Mrs. Stantons
paper at the Emma
Juillard Congress - Mrs
Russell Sage Presiding -
attended reception at
Mrs McCormicks this P.M. -
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony read Mrs. Stanton's paper at the Emma Juillard Congress, attended a reception at Mrs. McCormick's in the afternoon, and Mrs. Russell Sage presided over the event.

at Bloomington Ill -
Chautauqua -
Dear Rachel arrived at

entries.fullText:
Fine "at home" this eve'g &
Rachel was with us -
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony spent a fine evening at home with Rachel.

Mrs Sewalls -'at home-
not so many present - because
of her reception at the
Indiana Building tomorrow
night = to meet Mr Edmund
Russell - Rachel was present -

entries.fullText:
Went to Edgewater -
with dear Rachel -
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony went to Edgewater with Rachel.

entries.fullText: Spent day at the Fair with dear Rachel - & went home with her to Edgewater - dear mother Rosa told me of her spiritual communings
entries.summaryText: Spent day at the Fair with Rachel and went home with her to Edgewater. Rosa told me of her spiritual communings.

entries.fullText: Spent day at the Fair with dear Rachel - & went home with her to Edgewater - dear mother Rosa told me of her spiritual communings
entries.summaryText: Spent day at the Fair with Rachel and went home with her to Edgewater. Rosa told me of her spiritual communings.

entries.fullText: Dear Rachel - left for Phila this P.M. at 3. O'clock - we spent A.M. at the Fair -
entries.summaryText: Rachel left for Phila at 3 PM. We spent the morning at the Fair.

entries.fullText:
At 3. P. M. Cousin Jessie
Anthony & self went out to Lake
Geneva - cousin Hannah Boyles -
- & cousin Nathan Dickinsons
entries.summaryText: Cousin Jessie Anthony and Susan B. Anthony went to Lake Geneva with cousin Hannah Boyles and cousin Nathan Dickinsons.

entries.fullText:
At Lake Geneva
this P.M. Mrs. E. D. Harkus
came across the Lake for
me to go over to spend night
with her - Mrs Pinkerton-Chalmers
came with her steam yacht --
Mrs B. had 20 or 30 friends & I told
old incidents of my work till 10 oclock
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony spent the afternoon at Lake Geneva and was invited to spend the night with Mrs. E. D. Harkus. Mrs. Pinkerton-Chalmers arrived with her steam yacht and Mrs. B. had 20 or 30 friends over. Susan talked about old incidents of her work until 10 o'clock.

entries.fullText:
Mrs B had Mrs Chalmers - Mrs
Pinkerton & Mrs Adams to a
9 o'clock breakfast - and
after it Mrs Chalmers took
us to the village & left me
at Prof. Irving's Landing- & I
stopped this night with cousin
Hannah Boyles again -
entries.summaryText: Mrs. Chalmers, Mrs. Pinkerton, and Mrs. Adams had breakfast with Mrs. B. and then Mrs. Chalmers took them to the village. Susan was left at Prof. Irving's Landing and stayed the night with cousin Hannah Boyles again.

entries.fullText:
Cousin Jessie & self
went into Chicago this A.M.
- I left satchel at 67 Maple
- & then went down to
fair grounds - no - went
to Art Palace - to the Lake
meetings -& heard Henry George
& Father McGlynn -
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony and Cousin Jessie went to Chicago. Susan left her satchel at 67 Maple and then went to the Art Palace and Lake meetings where she heard Henry George and Father McGlynn.

entries.fullText:
At Mrs Sewalls - 67 Maple St -
spent A.M. with Mrs Sewall - in
Italian corner of Liberal Arts Building
- Lunched in Castle Donegal - with
young man from London-
Cousin Melissa Dick & Jessie Anthony
at Mrs Sewalls reception this evening - also
Phebe Fort - niece of Phebe Jones -
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony spent the morning with Mrs. Sewall in the Italian corner of the Liberal Arts Building. She had lunch in Castle Donegal with a young man from London. In the evening, she attended Mrs. Sewall's reception with Cousin Melissa Dick, Jessie Anthony, and Phebe Fort, niece of Phebe Jones.

entries.fullText:
Left Theo. L. & May Wright
Sewalls - at 2.P.M. for
Rock Island Depot - found
Mrs Chapman & Mrs DeVoe there.
Mrs Diggs not there - she came
on the 6. P.M. train - we left
on the 8 oclock -
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony left Theo. L. & May Wright Sewalls at 2 P.M. for Rock Island Depot. She found Mrs. Chapman and Mrs. DeVoe there, but Mrs. Diggs was not there yet. They left on the 8 o'clock train.

entries.fullText:
Arrived Kansas City Mo - at
8.05 - met ladies there - who
took us over to the K.C. Kansas
side - Hotel Amon - rather
poor-folks looking - many ladies
called - meeting at evening - a good
audience of a 1,000 or more
Mrs Chapman spoke beautifully -
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony arrived in Kansas City, Missouri and attended a meeting where Mrs. Chapman spoke beautifully.

entries.fullText:
at K.C. Kansas - meetings - A.M
P.M. & evening - Mrs [?] did
well - Mrs Hoffman ditto - Mrs Johns
tired & worried - but did wonderfully well
- 1600 at evening session - my speech came
last & ended at 10.20 - heard
one say - "she's a real Gladstone"!!
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony attended meetings in K.C. Kansas and gave a speech that ended at 10:20 PM, which was well received.

entries.fullText:
Called on Mrs Johns an
hour - & took train at 10.50 -
found Mrs Cushing at Station
- arrived Leavenworth - &
found brothers D.R. & Merritt at.
Depot - Merritt took 10.15, night
train for Huron - where overlook
brother D.R.'s farm & men - his
Maude has hay-fever badly —
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony visited Mrs. Johns and then traveled to Leavenworth to meet her brothers D.R. and Merritt.

entries.fullText:
at brother D.R.'s -
weather very hot & a fearfully
hot wind - so no one
wanted to step out in
the sun - Dannie - D.R. J.
left at - 9 - for Nebraska - with
Tony on a Prairie chicken
hunting excursion -
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony spent time at her brother D.R.'s place and Dannie and D.R. J. went on a hunting excursion.

entries.fullText:
at Brother D.R.'s - Leavenworth Kan
weather very hot - Arthur
Mosher came last night to [?]
& left this A.M. at 8.50 -
- For 10 days - the itching
on my back & all above waist
has kept up - but is growing
less & less - these few days —
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony spent time at her brother D.R.'s place and Arthur Mosher visited her.

Kansas City - Kan -
Mrs Fannie Reid Slusser
County Supt - Public Schools - Wyandotte
Dined with Mrs Cobbe
Downs - Mrs Dr Root - there - both
were in the old campaign of 1867 -
with Mrs Taylor, Mrs Nichols, Mrs
Armstrong - left on 5.40 train -
spent night Senator Dick [?lues] -
at [?] —
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony dined with Mrs. Fannie Reid Slusser and Mrs. Cobbe Downs and spent the night with Senator Dick [?lues].

- Mr Snoddy drove me over to Mound City -

Mrs - Smith - mother of Howard -
- Mr Carbon - drove Mrs Riggs & self

and slept at brother J.M.s at Fort Scott

may L. called on

- arrived P. at 7. stay with

arrangements for speaking -

Left Topeka at 7.30 - for
Leavenworth -

Left Leavenworth at 8.30
for Lawrence - to meet
Mrs De Voe in her meeting
- We were guests of Prof & Mrs
Carruth - walked home after
the Lectures & blistered my left
big toe joint !!
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony attends the Kansas State Fair and meets with various people in Topeka, Leavenworth, and Lawrence.

entries.fullText:
Visited Miss Sarah Brown
at Indian school in A.M. &
took train for R.C. and then
Santa Fe train for Chicago -
met Mr Johns in Depot at R.C.
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony visits Miss Sarah Brown at Indian school and takes a train to Chicago with Mr Johns.

entries.fullText:
Arrived Chicago at
9:20 A.M - and went
direct to dear Mrs L.E.
Grass - stopping at Walton
flats to take my trunk
[?][?] - found a warm
welcome "home" from brother M & Mrs
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony arrives in Chicago and goes to Mrs L.E. Grass's house, stopping at Walton flats to take her trunk.

entries.fullText:
Cecilian Circle - 4 P.M.
393 - Jackson Boulevard -
Mrs (FF) Rose L. Colby
Found Next to [?] in a
[?] "Mothers" [Juslitheter]
entries.summaryText: Attended Cecilian Circle meeting with Mrs (FF) Rose L. Colby at 393 Jackson Boulevard.

entries.fullText:
Lucy Stove dies this evening at
her home - Rochester, Mass. aged 76 -
I can but wonder if the spirit now sees things as it did 25 years ago??
entries.summaryText: Lucy Stove passed away at her home in Rochester, Mass. at the age of 76.

entries.fullText: Mrs May Wright Sewall came this evening - very late - but followed us - Mr & Mrs G. to Theatre to see Irving & Terry in Sir Thomas Becket - it was very fine Lucy Stone died - this night -
entries.summaryText: Mrs May Wright Sewall came this evening to see a play with us. Lucy Stone died this night.

entries.fullText: Mrs May Wright Sewall spoke this A.M in W. B. Assembly Room - to a small and changing audience - She read her speech - . Niece Guelma McL. Baker came this A.M. & niece Lucy E. met & took her to Cousin [?]
entries.summaryText: Mrs May Wright Sewall spoke in the morning to a small audience. Niece Guelma McL. Baker came to visit.

entries.fullText: Mrs Sewall spent the day at the Fair Grounds - & in talking with Mr Clarence Young about editing the report of Womens Congress Anna Shaw & Lucy E. stopped at Mrs Gross & took train for Phila - we all heard Lady Henry Somerset at 3. P.M. -
entries.summaryText: Mrs Sewall spent the day at the Fair Grounds and talked with Mr Clarence Young. Anna Shaw and Lucy E. left for Phila. We all heard Lady Henry Somerset speak.

entries.fullText: Spent A.M. witnessing contract between Mr Young & Mrs Sewall - after Luncheon went to the grounds & there found Brother Merritt had just arrived from Huron - [?]
entries.summaryText: Witnessed a contract between Mr Young and Mrs Sewall in the morning. Brother Merritt arrived in the afternoon.

entries.fullText:
Guest of Mr Sam'l C. &
Mrs Emily Maud Brown - Gross -
from Oct. 8 to Nov. 2 -
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony is a guest of Mr. Sam'l C. and Mrs. Emily Maud Brown-Gross from October 8 to November 2.

entries.fullText:
Woman's Building - Assembly room
The benefits of Organization
Mrs James V. Eagle - manager -
- Miss Hultin spoke before me -
- & I told the damages from
non-organization &c - Mrs
Colby - failed to come - after I
had worked hard to get the place
for her -
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony speaks about the benefits of organization at the Woman's Building - Assembly room. Mrs. James V. Eagle and Miss Hultin also spoke. Mrs. Colby failed to come after Susan had worked hard to get the place for her.

entries.fullText:
Mrs Sewall came again
this evening - niece
Gulie with me at Mrs Gross -
entries.summaryText: Mrs. Sewall visits Susan B. Anthony again and Susan's niece, Gulie, is with her at Mrs. Gross's place.

entries.fullText:
All the Organization Room
Representatives spoke of their
societies in turn - before
Mrs Palmer & the Road - & Mrs
P. held reception in evening -
Mrs Sewall spoke for [Convert?]
& I for suffrage - the Mayor of
Chicago - Carter Harrison - shot this day -
entries.summaryText: Representatives from all the Organization Room societies spoke before Mrs. Palmer and the Road. Mrs. Palmer held a reception in the evening. Mrs. Sewall spoke for [Convert?] and Susan B. Anthony spoke for suffrage. The Mayor of Chicago, Carter Harrison, was shot on this day.

entries.fullText:
Went to Depot - with
Mrs S. to take 1 P.M train
& found it taken off - so she
went back & took the 11 P.M. train
Brother Merritt & niece Guelie
dined - & brother Merritt took
the P.M. train for Fort Scott -
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony goes to the Depot with Mrs. S. to take the 1 P.M. train but it was taken off, so Mrs. S. took the 11 P.M. train. Susan's brother, Merritt, and niece, Guelie, dined with her and Merritt took the P.M. train for Fort Scott.

entries.fullText:
Mrs Gross and self went to the
grounds - & spent evening in the
Court of Honore - Niece Gulie with
us - the illumination - the fountains
most lovely - This was my last
sight of the white City in
its full glory by night -
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony and Mrs. Gross go to the grounds and spend the evening in the Court of Honore with Susan's niece, Gulie. They see the illumination and the fountains, which were most lovely. This was Susan's last sight of the white City in its full glory by night.

entries.fullText:
Mrs Palmer gave her farewill
address in W.B. Assembly Room
at 11. this A.M. - Mrs G. & self
missed it - to our great regret -
entries.summaryText: Mrs Palmer gave her farewell address in W.B. Assembly Room.

entries.fullText:
Trying to gather myself
together - to start for home -
Carter Harrisons funeral at 10 - &
the hearse never reached Graceland
until after 5 P.M. Mrs Gross - in her
lovely [??ke] - with her lovely red horses -
drove me out - & we walked into the
cemetery -
entries.summaryText: Attended Carter Harrison's funeral and visited Graceland cemetery with Mrs Gross.

entries.fullText:
Packed trunk & Mrs G.
took me to Mich. Central Depot -
for 6 P.M. train - her affection
& attention are phenomenal -
entries.summaryText: Packed trunk and Mrs G. took me to Mich. Central Depot.

entries.fullText: Reached Rochester about - 11. A.M.
entries.summaryText: Reached Rochester around 11 A.M.

entries.fullText: [No entry for this date]
entries.summaryText: No entry for this date.

entries.fullText:
[Didn't] Yes - I went to
State school? --
entries.summaryText: Went to State school.

entries.fullText:
Balanced accounts with Sister
Mary for Aug. Sept. Oct. & begin - Nov
with with $50. from Powers Bank -
Mrs Greenleaf called & talked
election chances - she needs fully
2,000 Republican votes to elect her -
entries.summaryText: Balanced accounts with Sister Mary and talked election chances with Mrs Greenleaf.

entries.fullText:
Election Day -
The Democrats here snowed
under this time -
Mrs. Greenleaf ran several
hundred ahead of
the Dem. ticket in this count
entries.summaryText: Democrats won the election, but Mrs. Greenleaf ran ahead of the Democratic ticket.

entries.fullText:
Took train for New York -
Telegram from Mrs [St??sbur?]
Denner - said woman suffrage
carried by 3,000- majority -
entries.summaryText: Took train to New York and received a telegram saying woman suffrage carried by 3,000 majority.

entries.fullText:
Reached No. 10. East 68th st
New York two hours late -
- but had a cup of coffee & bread
& butter -
entries.summaryText: Arrived two hours late in New York and had a cup of coffee and bread and butter.

entries.fullText:
In New York - writing
or helping Mrs Stanton
write resolutions & Plan
of work for the Con -
entries.summaryText: Helping Mrs Stanton write resolutions and plan of work for the Con.

entries.fullText:
Working all the day
with Mrs Stanton - and
returning at night to sleep
at cousin Semantha's
Dined this evening with
Mrs. & Katie Blake -
entries.summaryText: Working all day with Mrs Stanton, returning to sleep at cousin Semantha's, and dining with Mrs. and Katie Blake in the evening.

entries.fullText:
Cousin Samantha, Mrs Stone,
self went to Prof Felix Adlers.
Carnagie Hall - 57th st & 7th Ave
to hear Wm Dudley Foulke - on the
degradation of the suffrage & its cures -
entries.summaryText: Attended a lecture by Wm Dudley Foulke on the degradation of the suffrage & its cures.

entries.fullText:
N.Y. State - W.S.A. 25th annual
meeting in Historical Hall -
Brooklyn - Business meeting
of officers & delegates at Pier -
Point Hotel - sister May & self
guests of Mrs Mariana M. [?]
160 Hicks Street - [?] to Brooklyn
called on Charles A Dana - who
[?] 100,000 signatures to petition Wash
about [?]
entries.summaryText: Attended the N.Y. State - W.S.A. 25th annual meeting in Brooklyn and visited Charles A Dana.

entries.fullText:
N.Y. State Con - in session
H.B. Blackwell came in - in the
P.M. session - supped at Mrs. C's -
also Aaron M. Powell & wife -
Dr Stone opened the evening session
with prayer - Julia Ward Howe
Powell & [?] Christensen spoke.
entries.summaryText: Attended the N.Y. State Con and heard speeches by Julia Ward Howe, Powell, and [?] Christensen.

entries.fullText:
N.Y. State Con in session -
Elizabeth Oakes Smith - died
this day at Hollywood, N.C.
at her daughter in law's - Mrs
Augusta Oak Smith - her son
died five years ago-
entries.summaryText: Attended the N.Y. State Con and learned about the death of Elizabeth Oakes Smith.

entries.fullText:
Executive Comm. meeting at
Mr Pierpoint House -
Mrs. Isaac Carey gave
a lovely reception to the officers
& delegates & local members of
the [?] - In evening Mrs Greenleaf
& self spoke at special meeting
at the city [?] - Mrs Blakes -
entries.summaryText: Attended an Executive Comm. meeting and a reception hosted by Mrs. Isaac Carey.

entries.fullText:
Meeting of the [Dusiners?]
Committee - the 7. General officers
at Murry Hill Hotel - in the Y's
room - Mrs Danker & self
lunched with Mrs G - I went to
Mrs Stantons- & cousin Samantha
brought Mrs G. to call - & Mrs G. staid
the evening - & I took her back
to her Hotel & then went to 68th St -
entries.summaryText: Attended a meeting of the [Dusiners?] Committee and had lunch with Mrs G.

entries.fullText:
On way to Mrs Stanton's
called on Mrs Russell Sage
50 - 5th Avenue - Cousin L. & sister
May went over to South Orange &
dined with cousin Ellen Hoxie
Squier - called on Mrs Curtis
& her daughter Mrs Bullard
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony visits Mrs. Russell Sage and her cousin L. on her way to Mrs. Stanton's. May dines with cousin Ellen Hoxie Squier in South Orange.

entries.fullText:
Dined with Dr Mary Putnam
Jacobi - then called at Mrs Stantons
found her out driving
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony dines with Dr. Mary Putnam Jacobi and visits Mrs. Stanton, but she is out driving.

entries.fullText:
Mrs Burt - Pres State W. C. T. U.
called at Cousin Samantha's - to talk
leaving our suffrage state canvass alone
with the suffrage exit - try to send out
no petitions for suffrage under W.C.T.U. headings
Started for Phila. Found at World
Building that Carrie C. Chapman had arrived
home from Colorado so went to see
her - & spent the night --
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony meets with Mrs. Burt and Cousin Samantha to discuss suffrage. She then travels to Philadelphia and spends the night with Carrie C. Chapman.

entries.fullText:
Left Mrs Chapmans - at
Bensonhurst at 9 A.M.,
reach Phila at 1 - Dined
at Dr Longshores - called at dear
Miss [?] - went in rain to
[?] - to find Rachel & [M????]
& Lucy going to Julia Marlowe - theatre
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony leaves Mrs. Chapman's and travels to Bensonhurst and then Philadelphia. She dines with Dr. Longshores and visits Miss [?]. She then goes to the theater with Rachel, Lucy, and [M????] to see Julia Marlowe.

entries.fullText:
Spent day with dear
Rachel at Somerton - R.
actually doing the cooking
for 10 in family - Grace Green
doing 2d girls march - Ground out
Ball for Wash Con - [?] [?] of
matches --
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony spends the day with Rachel in Somerton. Rachel cooks for a family of 10 while Grace Green prepares for the 2nd girls march and they ground out a ball for Wash Con.

entries.fullText:
The Pennsylvania W. S. A.
Convention - in Phila - in New
Century Club House Parlors -
Lucy E. [Mather?] R. & self went to
[?] - good audiences - Mrs
Cally came & spoke - Wyoming [?]
in evening - Mrs Blankenburg
presided [?] - dear Mary Green
spoke beautifully -
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony attends the Pennsylvania W.S.A. Convention in Philadelphia with Lucy E. [Mather?] R. and speaks to good audiences. Mrs. Cally and dear Mary Green also speak beautifully.

entries.fullText: Penna,, Su. B A , [?]
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony wrote a journal entry on November 24, 1893 from an unknown location in Pennsylvania.
Susan B. Anthony wrote a journal entry on November 25, 1893 from an unknown location.
Susan B. Anthony wrote a journal entry on November 26, 1893 from an unknown location.
Susan B. Anthony wrote a journal entry on November 27, 1893 from an unknown location.

Susan B. Anthony wrote a journal entry on November 29, 1893 from an unknown location.

entries.fullText:
Thanksgiving Dinner - & Mr & Mrs Gannetts -
sister Mary & self - Mr & Mrs Lamb -
[?] Prevot - & 3 young men - pleasant
time - called at Mr Thayers - & Mrs
Sanford's - Lovely, bright day - but
rain & snow in evening -
entries.summaryText: Thanksgiving dinner with friends and family, visited Mr. Thayers and Mrs. Sanford's.

entries.fullText: [Try on dress - Mrs Fullams]
entries.summaryText: Trying on a dress with Mrs. Fullams.

entries.fullText:
Our Dear Mother's 100th Birth day -
& when Jan 27/94 arrives - it will be
our dear father's 100th Birth day -
- Mary Hallowell & Sarah Willis
& Mrs Greenleaf to dinner with sister Mary
& self - Dec. 2d - used to be is so is to day
our Thanksgiving Day - I thought of all
the dear ones absent & those gone before
& those still this side
entries.summaryText: Celebrating mother's 100th birthday with family and friends.

entries.fullText: Go Mrs Fullam to try on dress -
entries.summaryText: Mrs. Fullam goes to try on a dress.

entries.fullText:
at Mrs Sanford's - to Luncheon 1. Oclock -
Mr & Mrs Greenleaf & Mr & Mrs
Sargent - it was Mr Sargent's
69th birth day
entries.summaryText: Attended a luncheon at Mrs. Sanford's for Mr. Sargent's 69th birthday with Mr. and Mrs. Greenleaf.

entries.fullText: At home
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony was at home.

entries.fullText:
Business meeting - Political Equality
Club - Chamber of Commerce - 2 - P.M.
Industrial & Educational Union at [?] -
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony attended a business meeting for the Political Equality Club, the Chamber of Commerce, and the Industrial & Educational Union.

entries.fullText:
Ethical Club meeting -
entirely forgot this meeting
In the evening was the Unitarian
Church sale & supper - and
a larger number [?] their [?]
before -
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony attended an Ethical Club meeting but forgot about it. In the evening, she attended a sale and supper at the Unitarian Church.

entries.fullText:
At home - working to get
Campaign started
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony worked on starting a campaign at home.

entries.fullText:
Spent the day visiting [?] schools at the
State Industrial School - The Primary
Boys - the girls - the Protestant Boys - Father
Barrington's Catholic Boys - & sister - boys
"The Heavenly Inheritance - the Golden Text -
- asked boys - what was the great inheritance
that came to all boys at 213 - & made a
good talk --
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony visited various schools at the State Industrial School, including the Primary Boys, girls, Protestant Boys, and Father Barrington's Catholic Boys. She gave a talk about the Heavenly Inheritance and asked the boys what the great inheritance was that came to all boys at 213.

entries.fullText:
Took new brocade dress to Mrs Fullam
- Mrs Greenleaf over to work for
Campaign -
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony took a new brocade dress to Mrs Fullam and had Mrs Greenleaf over to work on the campaign.

entries.fullText: At home -
entries.summaryText: At home.

entries.fullText:
Talked at Unitarian Church Parlors
on woman & world's fair & ended with an appeal
for women to work for N.J. Con.Con -
- before women's auxilliary - then
dined at Dr Stoddards - [?] wife
is daughter of Isaac Butts - her sister Mrs
Oathout & husband were there - a very
pleasant time - a Paliamentary drill club
of 20 women was in session - John George Fish -
[lunch?]
entries.summaryText: Talked at Unitarian Church Parlors on woman & world's fair, dined at Dr Stoddards with Isaac Butts' daughter and sister, and attended a Parliamentary drill club.

entries.fullText:
Went to Mrs Fullams to my new
blue woll dress - given me by Larisse & her
husband - Al James - very beautifully made - also
tried on silk - going to be splendid
entries.summaryText: Went to Mrs Fullams to try on a new dress given to her by Larisse and her husband.

entries.fullText:
Harriet Taylor Upton - Waren Ohio
is 39 years old to-day
[worked] No - Mary & self
dined at Mrs Greenleafs - & after
returning home - I packed trunk & took
9.20 train for New York --
entries.summaryText: Celebrated Harriet Taylor Upton's birthday in Waren Ohio, dined at Mrs Greenleafs, and packed for a trip to New York.

Wea. MON. DEC. 18, 1893 Ther.

Queens Co Con. Jamaica
entries.summaryText: Journal entry on December 18, 1893 from Queens Co Con. Jamaica.

entries.fullText:
Wea. TUESDAY 19 Ther.

Suffolk Co. Con. - Riverhead
entries.summaryText: Journal entry on December 19, 1893 from Suffolk Co. Con. - Riverhead.

Richmond Co Con. - Richmond -
entries.summaryText: Journal entry on December 20, 1893 from Richmond Co Con. - Richmond -.

entries.summaryText: Journal entry on December 21, 1893.

entries.fullText:
Wea. FRIDAY 22 Ther.

Foremothers Day - Dinner -
Jaegers Hall - Mad. Avenue & 59th Street --
entries.summaryText: Journal entry on December 22, 1893 from Jaegers Hall - Mad. Avenue & 59th Street --, regarding Foremothers Day dinner.

Wea. SATURDAY 23 Ther.

Women's Conference of the Ethical
Social - Felix Adlers - New York -
in School Room - 54th st -
entries.summaryText: Journal entry on December 23, 1893 from New York, regarding Women's Conference of the Ethical Social at Felix Adlers in School Room - 54th st.

Wea. TUESDAY 26 Ther.
Wea. WED. DEC. 27, 1893 Ther.

Wea. THURSDAY 28 Ther.
At 7.20 - attended adjourned
Quarterly meeting of state school board
of managers - in new Library room
J. Barnes offered resignation from position of
Chairman [?] Com. - & Executive Com -
[?] table
entries.summaryText: Attended adjourned Quarterly meeting of state school board of managers.

entries.fullText:
Wea. FRIDAY 29 Ther.
Mrs Greenleaf called
over - but not quite
entries.summaryText: Mrs Greenleaf called over.

entries.fullText:
Worked at home all the day -
with type writer - trying to get all
letters answered - so as to begin
the new year even -
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony worked from home all day with a typewriter, trying to answer all letters to start the new year fresh.

entries.fullText:
Took breakfast 8.20 - & reached
state school 9.15 - attended Catholic
Church - Father Harrington - a mere
stripling - all the forms & mummery
Greek to me - talked to the boys & girls
at close of service - told them nothing [?]
change the record of the past year - now
was the time to begin new books - & keep all on credit
side

MEMORANDA
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony attended Catholic Church and talked to the boys and girls at the close of service, encouraging them to start the new year fresh and keep everything on the credit side.

entries.fullText:
Mrs Emma Gilbert - (Loomis?)
wife of Mr P. B. Loomis - of
Jackson - Michigan - dear
niece Ann Eliza's
friend & sister artist
wrote me from her [?]
home - for 20 years - during
my tour in Michigan from
March 6. to 18 - 1893 --
entries.summaryText: Received a letter from Mrs. Emma Gilbert (Loomis?) of Jackson, Michigan, the wife of Mr. P. B. Loomis, who is the dear niece Ann Eliza's friend and sister artist. She wrote during my tour in Michigan from March 6 to 18, 1893.

The Different notes given
Sister Mary - 575 - 250 & 50
with the interest on them
amounted to $1,010 - I
paid her the $10 - then
gave her a new
note for $1,000. at
six percent -
$1,000 -
